Since you're ready for more, let's look at how we handle repetitive tasks and reusable logic. This is where the real power of programming kicks in—making the computer do the "boring" work for you.
4. Loops (Doing things repeatedly)
A for loop lets you run a block of code multiple times without rewriting it. Imagine you want to count to five:
for number in range(1, 6):
    print("Counting:", number)

5. Lists (Storing groups of items)
Instead of creating a new variable for every single item, you can use a List to keep them all in one "container."
fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Cherry"]

# Adding a new fruit
fruits.append("Orange")

print(fruits[0]) # This prints the first item: Apple

6. Functions (Reusable "Mini-Programs")
A function is a block of code that only runs when you "call" it. It’s like a recipe you save in a book and pull out whenever you need to cook that specific dish.
def greet_user(username):
    print("Welcome back, " + username + "!")

# Now we call the function
greet_user("Sarah")
greet_user("Mike")

How these pieces fit together
Every app you use—from Instagram to Spotify—is just thousands of these small building blocks stacked on top of each other.
Summary Table
| Concept | What it does | Real-world analogy |
|---|---|---|
| Variable | Stores a piece of data | A labeled storage box |
| List | Stores multiple items | A shopping list |
| If Statement | Makes a decision | A fork in the road |
| Loop | Repeats an action | Running laps on a track |
| Function | A reusable set of steps | A recipe card |
